\subsection{Point b)}
To do Bayesian interference we use a uniform prior $\pi(\mu) \propto 1$ on the global intercept and assume the precision parameters to be $\tau \sim \Gamma(\alpha, \alpha)$ and $\nu \sim \Gamma(\alpha, \alpha)$ where $\alpha, \tau$ and $\nu$ are independent. 
To derive the full conditionals for a Gibbs sampler, we start with the joint posterior density. We write out the full joint density $\pi(\mu,\gamma,\tau,\nu|y)$ using the independence of the prior and the hierarchical structure as:
$$\pi(\mu,\gamma,\tau,\nu|y) \propto \left(\prod_{i = 1}^{m} \prod_{j = 1}^{n_i}\pi(y_{ij}|\mu,\gamma_i,\tau)\right) \times \left(\prod_{i = 1}^{m}\pi(\gamma_i|\nu)\right) \times \pi(\mu) \times \pi(\tau) \times \pi(\nu).$$
Using the distributions, we get that
$$\pi(\mu,\gamma,\tau,\nu|y) \propto \tau^{N/2} \exp{\left(-\frac{\tau}{2}\sum_{i,j}(y_{ij}-\mu-\gamma_i)^2\right)}\cdot \nu^{m/2} \exp{\left(-\frac{\nu}{2}\sum_i \gamma_i^2\right)} \cdot 1 \cdot \tau^{\alpha - 1} e^{-\alpha r} \cdot \nu^{\alpha - 1}.$$

\vspace{12pt}
\noindent We continue with finding the full conditional for $\mu$ by taking only terms in joint posterior that contain $\mu$:
$$\pi(\mu|y,\gamma,\tau,\nu) \propto \exp{\left(-\frac{\tau}{2}\sum_{i,j}(y_{ij}-\mu-\gamma_i)^2\right)}.$$
Let $N + \sum_i n_i$. We expand the quadratic equation and complete the square relative to $\mu$. This is a standard Normal kernel. The precision is the coefficient of $-\frac{1}{2}\mu^2$, which is $N \tau$ and the mean is the value that minimizes the sum of squares, so our distribution is
$$\mu|y,\gamma,\tau,\nu \sim N\left(\frac{1}{N}\sum_{i,j}(y_{ij} - \gamma_i),\frac{1}{N \tau}\right).$$

\vspace{12pt}
\noindent We want to find the full conditional for $\gamma_i$. For a specific cluster $i$, we gather terms containing $\gamma_i$. We note that $\gamma_i$ appears in the likelihood for all $j$ observations in that cluster and in its own random effect prior:
$$\pi(\gamma|y,\mu,\tau,\nu) \propto \exp{\left(-\frac{\tau}{2}\sum_{j = 1}^{n_i}(y_{ij} - \mu - \gamma_i)^2-\frac{\nu}{2}\gamma_i^2\right)}.$$
The exponent is a sum of two quadratics in $\gamma_i$. Precision is a sum of the individual precisions, so $n_i \tau + \nu$, and the mean is a weighted average, so $\frac{\tau \sum_{j}(y_{ij} - \mu) + \nu(0)}{n_i \tau + \nu}$. The distribution is then
$$\gamma_i|y,\mu,\tau,\nu \sim N\left(\frac{\tau \sum_{j = 1}^{n_i}(y_{ij} - \mu)}n_i \tau + \nu}, \frac{1}{n_i \tau + \nu}\right).$$

\vspace{12pt}
\noindent We want to find the full conditional for $\tau$. We isolate terms with $\tau$ and get:
$$\pi(\tau|y,\gamma,\mu,\nu) \propto \tau^{N/2}\exp{\left(-\frac{\tau}{2}\sum_{i,j}(y_{ij}-\mu-\gamma_i)^2\right)} \cdot \tau^{\alpha - 1}e^{-\alpha \tau}.$$
We combine the powers of $\tau$ and the terms in the exponent to get:
$$\pi(\tau|y,\gamma,\mu,\nu) \propto \tau^{(\alpha + N/2)-1}\exp{\left(-\tau\left(\alpha + \frac{1}{2}\sum_{i,j}(y_{ij}-\mu - \gamma_i\right)\right)}.$$
We recognize the kernel of a Gamma distribution and get:
$$\tau|y,\gamma,\mu,\nu \sim \Gamma\left(\alpha + \frac{N}{2}, \alpha + \frac{1}{2} \sum_{i,j} (y_{ij}-\mu -\gamma_i)^2\right).$$

\vspace{12pt}
\noindent Lastly, we want to find the full conditional for $\nu$, isolating the terms with $\nu$ we get:
$$\pi(\nu|y,\gamma,\mu,\tau) \propto \nu^{m/2} \exp{\left(-\frac{\nu}{2}\sum_{i = 1}^m \gamma_i^2\right)}\cdot \nu^{\alpha - 1}e^{-\alpha \nu}.$$
Similarly as before, combining terms gives:
$$\nu|y,\gamma,\mu,\tau \sim \Gamma\left(\alpha + \frac{m}{2}, \alpha + \frac{1}{2}\sum_{i = 1}^m \gamma_i^2\right).$$


\subsection{Point c)}
\noindent We implement Gibbs sampler in R. We let $\theta = (\mu, \gamma_1, \ldots, \gamma_m, \tau, \nu)$ be the vector of all unknown parameters and we want to draw samples from the joint posterior $\pi(\theta|y) \propto \pi(y|\theta) \pi(\theta)$. The Gibbs sampler moves from state $\theta^{(s)}$ to $\theta^{(s + 1)$ by updating each component one by one, conditioned on the most recent values of all other components. For algorithm, we need data $y_{ij}$, hyperparameters $\alpha$ and number of total iterations $S$. Based on that we want it to return a sequence of samples $\{\mu^{(s)}, \gamma^{(s)}, \tau^{(s)}, \nu^{(s)}\}_{s = 1}^S$ that represents the posterior distribution. 

\vspace{12pt}
\noindent We first set the initial values for all parameters at $s = 0$ as $\mu^{(0)} = mean(y), \gamma_i^{(0)} = 0$ for all $i = 1, \ldots, m$, $\tau^{(0)} = 1$ and $\nu^{(0)} = 1$. For iterations $s = 1, \ldots, S$, where obviously $S = 20000$, we update parameters based on the previous full conditionals from point b) as:

\begin{align*}
\mu^{(s)} &\sim N \left( \frac{1}{N} \sum_{i,j} (y_{ij} - \gamma_i^{(s-1)}), \frac{1}{N \tau^{(s-1)}} \right) \\
\gamma_i^{(s)} &\sim N \left( \frac{\tau^{(s-1)} \sum_{j=1}^{n_i} (y_{ij} - \mu^{(s)})}{n_i \tau^{(s-1)} + \nu^{(s-1)}}, \frac{1}{n_i \tau^{(s-1)} + \nu^{(s-1)}} \right), \quad i = 1, \dots, m \\
\tau^{(s)} &\sim \Gamma \left( \alpha + \frac{N}{2}, \alpha + \frac{1}{2} \sum_{i,j} (y_{ij} - \mu^{(s)} - \gamma_i^{(s)})^2 \right) \\
\nu^{(s)} &\sim \Gamma \left( \alpha + \frac{m}{2}, \alpha + \frac{1}{2} \sum_{i=1}^m (\gamma_i^{(s)})^2 \right)
\end{align*}

\noindent Then, the algorithm stores the vectors of parameters $\theta^{(s)}$ as the $s$-th row of result matrix. The returned matrix is of dimension $20000 \times (m+3)$, as we have the parameters $\mu, \gamma_1, \gamma_2, \ldots, \gamma_m, \tau, \nu$, but we decide to store corresponding variances $1/\mu$ and $1/\tau$ instead of parameters $\nu$ and $\tau$ as proposed by the instructions.

<<problem2c, fig.width=5, fig.height=4, eval=FALSE, out.width='0.7\\textwidth'>>=
library(coda)
run_gibbs <- function(data, alpha, iterations, prior_type = "gamma") {
  y <- data$y
  group <- as.numeric(as.factor(data$i))
  m <- max(group)
  N <- length(y)
  ni <- as.numeric(table(group))
  
  mu <- mean(y)
  gamma <- rep(0, m)
  tau <- 1
  nu <- 1
  
  samples <- matrix(NA, iterations, m + 3)
  colnames(samples) <- c("mu", paste0("gamma", 1:m), "var_eps", "var_gamma")
  
  for (s in 1:iterations) {
    mu_mean <- sum(y - gamma[group]) / N
    mu <- rnorm(1, mu_mean, sqrt(1 / (N * tau)))
    
    sum_y_mu <- tapply(y - mu, group, sum)
    prec_gamma <- ni * tau + nu
    mean_gamma <- (tau * sum_y_mu) / prec_gamma
    gamma <- rnorm(m, mean_gamma, sqrt(1 / prec_gamma))
    
    ss_eps <- sum((y - mu - gamma[group])^2)
    ss_gamma <- sum(gamma^2)
    
    if (prior_type == "gamma") {
      tau <- rgamma(1, alpha + N / 2, alpha + 0.5 * ss_eps)
      nu <- rgamma(1, alpha + m / 2, alpha + 0.5 * ss_gamma)
    } else if (prior_type == "mh_logist") {
      tau_prop <- rgamma(1, N / 2, 0.5 * ss_eps)
      ratio_tau <- (tau_prop * (tau + nu)^2) / (tau * (tau_prop + nu)^2)
      if (runif(1) < ratio_tau) tau <- tau_prop
      
      nu_prop <- rgamma(1, m / 2, 0.5 * ss_gamma)
      ratio_nu <- (nu_prop * (nu + tau)^2) / (nu * (nu_prop + tau)^2)
      if (runif(1) < ratio_nu) nu <- nu_prop
    }
    
    samples[s, ] <- c(mu, gamma, 1/tau, 1/nu)
  }
  return(as.mcmc(samples))
}

res_c <- run_gibbs(data, 0.0001, 20000)
@

\subsection{Point d)}
Solved in R. When running the sampler with the small $\alpha$, we expect the posterior means for $\mu$, $\sigma_{\epsilon} = 1/\tau$ and $\sigma_{\gamma}^2 = 1/\nu$ to be very close to the Maximum Likelihood Estimates obtained in part $a$. We use 20000 iterations and are looking for the indicator that the chain has converged and is exploring the posterior distribution efficiently.
We get the results of the posterior mean of $\mu$ to be 10.188965, of $1/\tau$ to be 0.800129 and of $1/\nu$ to be 0.246184. 

\begin{center}
