\vspace{6pt}
\noindent The Bayesian estimate is almost identical to the MLE which is expected because a flat prior $\pi(\mu) \propto 1$ is used, meaning that the data dominate the estimate. The Bayesian posterior means of both variances are slightly higher than MLE estimates. The plots of $\mu$ and $1/\tau$ look normal as they are centered around a stable mean with no visible trends of drifting which suggests excellent convergence and mixing. On the other hand, while we see that the $1/\nu$ has converged, we also see that the trace of it is more spikier. It frequently drops down to close to zero and then jumps up, indicating that the sampler is exploring a region where the random effect variance is nearly non-existent. This suggests that the data allow for the possibility that the group-level variation is negligible.

\subsection{Point e)}
The proportion of the variance explained by the random effect is $p = \frac{\nu^{-1}}{\nu^{-1}+\tau^{-1}} = \frac{\tau}{\nu + \tau}$. Given $\nu, \tau \sim \Gamma(\alpha,\alpha)$ independently, we know that $p = \frac{\tau}{\nu + \tau}$ follows a Beta distribution:
$$p \sim Beta(\alpha,\alpha).$$
The posterior mean for the proportion of variance $p$ is 0.2261526. The density plot shows a bump near 0.2 but is also has a strange behavior near 0. Regarding the prior, when $\alpha = 0.0001$, the density of the $Beta(0.0001,0.0001)$ is extremely concentrated at the boundaries, so near 0 and 1, where it spikes to infinity, and is 0 elsewhere. In my opinion, a $Beta(0.0001,0.0001)$ prior does not reasonably represent personal beliefs. This represents a very prior belief that either the group effect is non-existent ($p \approx 0$) or the error is non-existent ($p \approx 1$). This is usually not a reasonable prior as it penalizes intermediate values of $p$ where most real-world data actually lies.

<<problem2e, fig.width=5, fig.height=4, eval=FALSE, out.width='0.7\\textwidth'>>=
